Part 1 of Build A Simple File Explorer in Rust
Tutorial

Part 1 of Build A Simple File Explorer in Rust

5 steps

In this tutorial, you will start by initialising the project, prepare the project structure, and write a software architecture documentation and a README file.

As the tutorial progresses, you will write an initial mock implementation of the project by building a library that extends or integrates the usage of the path and fs modules of Rust's standard library.

Before we begin, ensure that you have followed the prerequisites!

Let's start here!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Rust Basics.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.
  • Recommended to know Git and GitHub. For a tutorial, head to Version Control Basics with Git and GitHub. Git must be installed and configured before doing this tutorial.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain the scope of the simple file explorer.
  • Understand the initial project structure.
  • Write initial documentation.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: Preparing Your Development Environment

    Ensure that you have the Rust toolchain installed. Head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.

    Ensure that you have Git installed and GitHub account setup for this project as you will be running commands or committing your code changes using a version control system called Git. If you are not familiar with Git and GitHub, head to Version Control Basics with Git and GitHub.

    We recommend using VSCode throughout this tutorial series as it is beginner-friendly and has a lot of plugins you can use. To help you with development, install the Rust Analyzer plugin for Visual Studio Code.

    Let's test that you have installed Git and Rust correctly by running the following commands

    Let's test that you have installed Git and Rust correctly by running the following commands

    git --version
cargo --version

    It should give you an output similar to the screenshot below.

    Create a new local git repository called simple-file-explorer. You can do so by running the following command.

    git init simple-file-explorer

    Select the newly created directory called simple-file-explorer with VSCode or run the following command. The command, however, may open a new window with the simple-file-explorer directory as the root directory.

    code simple-file-explorer

    Run the following command.

    cargo new --lib libfile-explorer

    This creates a new Rust crate called libfile-explorer inside the root directory of the project.

    Test the initialised project really works by running the following commands.

    cd libfile-explorer
cargo test

    It should output similar to the screenshot below.

    If that works, you can now proceed to the next step.

  • Step 2: Writing Initial Documentation

    Most of the time when writing a project, we initially write the implementation outright to test things out. It's not incorrect but it leaves a lot of implementation details that can be easily forgotten. Therefore, in this step, you will focus on writing the initial documentation of the project.

    Writing The README

    A README file is important because it introduces the project, explains its purpose, and provides essential information for users and contributors.

    It typically includes setup instructions, usage examples, and any required dependencies, making it easier for others to understand, install, and use the project without needing to examine the source code. A good README also outlines how others can contribute, helping foster collaboration and trust.

    Ultimately, it serves as a guide and reference point, improving the accessibility and professionalism of any software project.

    To create one, first create a file called README.md at the root directory of your project or you can run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    code README.md

    Today, modern AI tools allow you to articulate your project better such as VSCode's built-in Copilot feature. It is up to you if you are going to use that. For now, you will be just copying what was written below to your README file.

    # Simple File Explorer

This project is a simple file explorer. A file explorer is an application that allows navigation of the file system with an interactive GUI.

## Goals of the project

- Create a Rust library crate that can be easily interfaced with any language. It provides an API that allows reading the system's filesystem.
- Provide an OS-agnostic library crate by extending the `path` and `fs` modules from the Rust's `std`.
- Since it is _mostly_ OS-agnostic, developers can build GUIs around it with any language that can support different operating systems e.g. a GUI frontend built with Typescript/Javascript and web technologies.

## Non-goals of the project

- This project does not aim to replace already reputable file explorers such as the Windows File Explorer, MacOS Files, and the well known file explorers on Linux such as Gnome Nautilus, and Thunar.
- Archiving and compression features are not part of the project's scope.
    Markdown

    Save the README.md file. Read carefully the contents of the file to have a better understanding of what the project could be from the start to finish.

    Based on the README, the project is a cross-platform Rust library that provides an API for reading and navigating the file system.

    Writing The Software Architecture Documentation

    An ARCHITECTURE.md is typically used to document the high-level design and structure of a software project. It explains how the system is organized, how its components interact, and the reasoning behind key design decisions. It is also better known as a Software Architecture Documentation.

    Here’s what it usually includes:

    • Overview of the system architecture (e.g. layered architecture, microservices, client-server)
    • Main components/modules and their responsibilities
    • Data flow or control flow between parts of the system
    • Key technologies or patterns used (e.g. REST APIs, message queues, event-driven design)
    • Design rationale explaining why certain decisions were made (e.g. trade-offs, performance considerations)
    • Diagrams to help visualize structure and relationships

    It’s especially useful for onboarding new developers, maintaining consistency as the codebase evolves, and aligning contributors on how things are built and why.

    Create a file called ARCHITECTURE.md at the root directory of your project e.g. by using VSCode or by running the following command.

    code ARCHITECTURE.md

    Write the following to your ARCHITECTURE.md file.

    # ARCHITECTURE

This document details different components of the code base. The intention is to provide a simple to explain but a high-level description of the projects goals and plans to each of these internal mechanisms.

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    fend["frontend client"] --> Javascript
    fend --> C["C or C++"]
	fend --> Rust
    subgraph sub["libfile-explorer"]
    a1[fs_wrappers] --> s1[file explorer core]
    c1[json_api] --> s1
    s1 --> prelude
    end
    sub --> fend
```

## Library

The library provides functions that extends or integrates the `fs` and `path` modules from the Rust
standard library, `std`. The library can be split into the following modules.

- `fs_wrappers` contains file operations that extend the functionality of the `fs` module.
- `json_api` contains the JSON API logic that accepts input and performs filesystem operations based on the input received.
- `prelude` contains most commonly exported functions. This is optional and possibly be removed if there is no benefit at all if including this.
    Markdown

    For now, the ARCHITECTURE.md is short and might be updated as the project progresses. You might notice that there is a code block there that signifies it is a Mermaid diagram. This code block will be rendered once you push those files on GitHub. Let's push your new files to GitHub in the next step.

  • Step 3: Pushing Your Code To GitHub

    In this step, it is required that you have a GitHub account and have set up your credentials properly. See prerequisites.

    Head to your GitHub page. Go to the upper-right of the page and create a new repository.

    You will be directed to the "Create new repository" page.

    Name the repository "simple-file-explorer" and click the "Create repository" button at the bottom-right.

    In your machine, create a .gitignore file inside the libfile-explorer directory. Write the following contents to the file.

    /target
    Plain text

    This will ensure that Git ignores the target directory that contains built artefacts.

    Run the following commands on your terminal. You need to configure your Git credentials first before running the following commands.

    git add -A
git commit -m 'initial commit'

    Replace "yourusername" with your GitHub username before running the next set of commands. We always recommend the SSH option as it is more secure. See the following GitHub documentation before proceeding.

    If you are using Personal Access Tokens and HTTPS.

    git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/simple-file-explorer.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

    If you are using SSH for your Git credentials.

    git remote add origin git@github.com:yourusername/simple-file-explorer.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

    Once pushed, your Mermaid code block will be rendered as a Mermaid diagram.

    Congratulations! You have pushed your files to GitHub. In the next step, you are going to write a mock implementation of the library. It won't be functional but it gives you an idea of what it could be as we progress the project.

  • Step 4: Initial Code Implementation

    For the initial mock implementation, head to the libfile-explorer directory and create a file inside the src directory called fs_wrappers.rs. Write the following code to the fs_wrappers.rs file.

    use std::fs;
use std::os::unix::fs::MetadataExt;
use std::path::PathBuf;
use std::path::Path;

/// A representation of what a filesystem has. For now, we have two kinds, it is either
/// a `Directory` or a `File`.
pub enum FsKind {
	Directory,
	File
}

/// A representation of a filesystem object. For now, it only contains important metadata.
/// This is an initial implementation and will change as the project progresses.
pub struct FsObject {
	pub kind: FsKind,
	pub date_created: String,
	pub size: u64
}

/// Initial implementation of the `FsObject` methods. For now, we have the `new` function
/// to create a new `FsObject`.
impl FsObject {
	pub fn new(path: Option<PathBuf>) -> FsObject {
		let kind: FsKind;
		let date_created: String;
		let size: u64;
		if let Some(p) = path {
			kind = if p.is_dir()  {
				FsKind::Directory
			} else if p.is_file() {
				FsKind::File
			} else {
				panic!("Filesystem kind is not supported yet")
			};
			let metadata = p.metadata().unwrap();
			let _date_created = metadata.created().unwrap();
			date_created = stringify!(date_created).to_string();
			size = metadata.size();
			return FsObject {
				kind,
				date_created,
				size
			}

		} else {
			// Assume that it's the current working directory
			let current_directory = std::env::current_dir().unwrap();
			let metadata = current_directory.metadata().unwrap();
			let _date_created = metadata.created().unwrap();
			date_created = stringify!(date_created).to_string();
			size = metadata.size();
			return FsObject {
				kind: FsKind::Directory,
				date_created,
				size
			}
		}
	}
}
    Rust

    Replace all contents of the file, lib.rs inside the src directory with the following code.

    pub mod fs_wrappers;
    Rust

    As explained in the code comments inside the fs_wrappers.rs file, the initial implementation is more like a framework of what the library could be.

    Since the project is a simple file explorer, users of the library should expect it's as simple as it gets. It gets two kinds of objects in the filesystem, a file and a directory (or folder). However, some basic functionalities are still needed as follows:

    • Move a file
    • Move a directory
    • Copy a file
    • Copy a directory
    • Delete a file
    • Delete a directory

    Functions for those functionalities can be attributed to what kind of object it is in the filesystem. Therefore, you can expect that the enum, FsKind will contain methods associated with the kind of object, a Directory or File. One might also just write those methods for the FsObject custom type by providing a match pattern with the FsKind enum.

  • Step 5: Stacking It Up!

    You have finished the first part of the tutorial series of Build A Simple File Explorer in Rust.

    You have prepared the initial project structure, the initial documentation of the project, and an initial code that gives you an idea of what the project could be in the future tutorials. Functionalities mentioned in the previous will be implemented in the next tutorial.

    If you have other questions and suggestions in improving this tutorial, feel free to send your feedback in our Discord server!
